arch:property.oc:show_val: Locus 12, 10 YR 5/4, (Munsell Yellowish Brown), is a compact, artifact-rich layer of moist, greasy soil. The clay-like stratum is patchy in areas and is difficult to separate from Locus 13. The locus contains bones, burnt residue, charcoal, limestone chips, plaster chips, shells, and some sand. Artifacts include coins, glass, tesserae, and metal nails. One Roman lamp was found in excellent condition. Pottery in Locus 12 varies, but large storage vessels are predominant; jars or jugs, cooking pots, and Nabataean fine wares are also common.
Locus 12 extends from the balk in the south to approximately two-thirds of the way towards the north wall. Here, the greasy layer becomes patchy and is replaced by Locus 15.
Locus 19 in the balk and Locus 15.

Period of abandonment. The arch is reused as a squatter's camp--collapsed stucco and architectural elements reused as a temporary floor level. A cache of Late Roman coins (Locus 11) was found associated with these levels.

Phase X: Site abandonment post major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c, Upper level robbing occurs including the upper treads of East and West Interior and Rear Staircases, and the associated upper landings. Evidence of squatter camps in the South Corridor and Central Arch.
